Work focused on integrating the video stream obtained from the ESP32-CAM into 
the existing virtual piano application. The MediaPipe-based hand detection system,
which had previously been developed for the computer's built-in camera, was modified 
to process frames received from the ESP32-CAM.

After decoding the incoming video frames in Python, each frame was processed using the 
MediaPipe Hands model. The coordinates of the detected hand landmarks were extracted 
and integrated with the previously developed virtual piano system. As a result, hand 
movements could be detected using the ESP32-CAM instead of the computer's built-in camera.

Several tests were performed to evaluate the effect of network latency on hand tracking 
performance. The influence of frame rate variations on detection accuracy was observed, 
and several code optimizations were implemented to achieve smoother real-time performance. 
The system was also tested under different lighting conditions to evaluate its overall reliability.
